Each index combines two traits into a single variable that takes the difference between ratings of the in-party and out-party candidates.\footnote{Throughout the rest of the paper, I will refer to these indices of differences as ``moral judgment,'' or the ``moral judgment index,'' and as ``competence judgment'' for simplicity.} I collapsed the trait ratings to emphasize only negative judgments because previous studies have shown that negative judgments are more influential and potent than positive \cite{Klein1996,Goren2002,Goren2007}. Small differences in the same direction are essentially meaningless (e.g. saying ``moral'' describes the Republican out-partisan quite well and the Democratic in-partisan extremely well), thus the variable focuses on perceptions with a different valence for each candidate (e.g. one is extremely or quite moral; the other is not too well or not at all). I use the difference between the in-partisan and the out-partisan to identify partisans who truly see gap between the morality and competence of the candidates. Judgments of candidate character tend to be comparisons between the major-party nominees \citeaffixed{Rahnetal1990}{see}. In many cases, these judgments are ambivalent \citeaffixed{Klein1991,Lavine2001,Sears1983}{see}. The indices are collapsed to indicate simply whether a respondent rated the out-party better than the in-party, rated the candidates ambivalently (no difference), or rated the in-party better than the out-party.\footnote{The scale originally ranged from -5 to 5. All values under zero were collapsed to -1 and all values above zero to 1. Zero was left as is, and indicates that the candidates were judged the same.}

Figure \ref{fig:distribution_moral_diff} shows the distribution of the moral judgment and competence judgment indices among partisans (pure independents excluded).\footnote{Figure \vref{fig:anes_distribution_moral_diff_gop} in the appendix shows the distribution of the moral rating indices for Republicans and Figure \ref{fig:anes_distribution_moral_diff_dem} for Democrats. The ratings are largely similar between the two parties.} Only \Sexpr{round(percents.partisan.weight[1],2)*100} percent of partisans think the other party's nominee is more moral than their own, which is similar to the \Sexpr{round(percents.partisan.weight2[1],2)*100} percent who think the out-partisan is more competent. However, most partisans perceived their party's candidate to be morally better (\Sexpr{round(percents.partisan.weight[3],2)*100}\%), which is a stark contrast to competence, where only \Sexpr{round(percents.partisan.weight2[3],2)*100} percent believe their nominee has the edge in competence. The majority of partisans actually see no meaningful difference between the candidates' competence (\Sexpr{round(percents.partisan.weight2[2],2)*100}\%), giving both the same rating. Most partisans are giving both candidates positive ratings on competence while giving the in-partisan positive marks on morality and the out-partisan negative marks on morality.

For the most part, partisans follow the same patterns of Figure \ref{fig:distribution_moral_diff}; however, Democrats are more likely to rate the in-partisan as more moral than Republicans (\Sexpr{round(dist.moral.dem[3],2)*100}\% vs. \Sexpr{round(dist.moral.gop[3],2)*100}\%). Despite Republicans ``owning'' morality while Democrats own empathy \cite{Hayes2005}, proportionally more Democrats think their candidate is different in valence on empathy than Republicans. Republicans are slightly more likely to be ambivalent or to prefer the out-partisan on morals. (See Figure \vref{fig:anes_distribution_moral_diff_gopdem} in the appendix).




\subsection{Covariates}
All models reported below include a number of covariates to account for alternative explanations for vote choice, especially defection across party lines. There are controls for perceptions of the candidate, for demographics, for political attitudes, and for candidate characteristics. Every variable, including the indices discussed above, is recoded to range from zero to one.\footmote{The age in years and age squared variables are the only exceptions. I left both on their original range of values.}

The most important covariate is the index of competence judgments. The competence control is two questions: an assessment of how well ``knowledgeable'' and ``intelligent'' describe the candidates. intelligence is asked every year except it was not asked of Senator Bob Dole in 1996. Therefore, the data is missing an out-party rating for Democrats in 1996, creating a gap in the ratings since 1984. However, the results are substantively similar if 1996 is excluded entirely. To avoid losing all that data, the index for only that year is one question; for all other years it is two.

The models also include controls for demographic factors, political factors, and candidate factors. Each control aims to account for an alternative explanation for political behavior. The demographic controls are age, gender,\footnote{Gender is coded zero for men and one for women} race,\footnote{Race is coded one for non-white respondents and zero for white respondents.} income,\footnote{Income is coded by thirds; refused are set to the median. Results are the same if refused is excluded.} education, and church attendance. The controls for political identification and attitudes are strength of party identification, strength of ideology, interest in the election, an index of issue positions,\footnote{Issue attitudes is an index ranging from zero to one of four issue questions that were asked in each year. The questions are attitudes toward defense spending, government aid to minorities/blacks, abortion, and government guarantees of jobs. The index is scaled such that agreement with one's own party equals one, and disagreement equals zero.} the respondents' perception of the out-party candidate's ideology, and whether respondents cares who wins the presidency.

All models also had a control for whether an out-party incumbent was standing for election, whether respondents were in the South, and whether Bill Clinton was a candidate. I control on Bill Clinton because he received the most negative ratings of integrity of any presidential candidate in the time frame of this study. Even Democrats rated President Clinton's integrity lowly. This control has the added positive benefit of also controlling for the two elections when Ross Perot ran strongly as a third-party candidate, which were elections with significantly higher rates of defection, especially among Republicans. Indifference and ambiguity toward the parties is a significant predictor of split-ticket voting \cite{Davis2014,Mulligan2011}, and the variables for caring who wins and ideological difference between the candidates help account for that.


\section{Moral Judgments and Presidential Vote Choice}
The first dependent variable I will examine is vote choice. This analysis focuses on determining the correlation between perceiving a large moral difference between the two parties and party loyalty at the ballot box. \citeasnoun{Haidt2012} argues that morals ``bind and blind,'' meaning they blind us to the shortcomings of our own ``tribe'' and increasing our in-group loyalty. If moral attitudes toward political actors have the hypothesized influence, if they exert a significant moral influence in their own right, then we should see that strong moral judgments influence those who hold them to be more loyal to their party. Conversely, those who do not see their party's nominee as morally superior will be less loyal.

%\subsection{Hypothesis: Moral judgment will make partisans more loyal to their party's candidates in both presidential and congressional elections}
