Figure \ref{fig:presvote_descriptive_diff} shows the bivariate relationship between moral judgment of presidential candidates and presidential vote. Each bar represents the average percentage of respondents in that category who report that they did not vote for their party's presidential candidate. Fully \Sexpr{pref.out.moral} percent of partisans who think the out-party is morally better than the in-party defect to the out-party. Only \Sexpr{pref.out.comp} percent defect when the out-partisan is seen as more competent. The \Sexpr{pref.out.moral - pref.out.comp} percentage point difference is statistically significant. Partisans who do not believe their nominee is morally better and actually before the out-partisan are significantly more likely to defect.

Partisans who are ambivalent about which candidate is most moral are also less loyal than those who are ambivalent regarding competence. The gap is much smaller than among those who prefer the out-party nominee (down to \Sexpr{ambig.moral - ambig.comp} percentage points), but it is still significant. Among those who favor the in-party on both morals and competence there is not a significant gap in percentage who defect. Partisans who do not see their side's candidate as morally better are significantly less loyal than partisans with similarly negative or ambiguous perceptions regarding competence. Candidates who fail to win convince members of their base that they are morally better lose support. 



\begin{figure}[htb]
  \centering
  \caption[Presidential Vote Choice by Difference in Judgment]{\textbf{Presidential Vote Choice by Difference in Moral and Competence Judgments}\\ \footnotesize \textit{Note}: Vote choice on the y-axis is coded as one if respondents cast a ballot for their out-party candidate (i.e. defected to the other party); it is zero otherwise. The bars show the percentage of respondents who defected to the out-party candidate for each bin of the moral judgment index.}\label{fig:presvote_descriptive_diff}
  {\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{DV_partisan_pres_combined-1.pdf}}
\end{figure}

The evidence in Figure \ref{fig:presvote_descriptive_diff} gives a first sense of how moral judgments drive. Without controlling for other factors, however, we cannot determine whether this correlation is valid. It is possible that another variable accounts for this relationship that is not present. To answer these doubts, the analysis now turns to multivariate regression models. I run a logistic regression model on vote choice, where a zero indicated that a respondent voted for the in-party candidate while a one indicates that he or she voted for another candidate or did not vote for president.\footnote{Data is included only for respondents who reported turning out to vote. Defecting can mean any of these alternatives: voted for the other party's candidate, voted for a third- party candidate, or did not cast a vote for president but did for other races.} Most partisans cast a ballot for their own party's candidate, but as we saw in Figure \ref{fig:presvote_descriptive_diff} the partisans who favor the out-party presidential candidate or are ambiguous between them are less loyal.\footnote{In a separate analysis not reported here, moral judgment have a small, significant effect on self-reported turnout. Judgments of competence have no effect. Partisans who thought the out-party candidate was more moral had about a 25\% change of not turning out. Ambivalent partisans had a 21\% chance of staying home. Partisans who believed their party's nominee was the most moral had only a 17\% chance of reporting they did not turn out. However, other variables, especially education, had strongers effects. It is likely the traditional resource-driven model of participation is a better explanation for turnout \citeaffixed{Bradyetal1995}{see}. Moral judgments are only a small part of this calculus. For this reason, the results are not covered here.} There is variation in loyalty at the ballot box that appears correlated with moral judgments. However, a regression analysis is needed to control for other factors. It may simply be that stronger partisans rank higher on moral judgment and are more loyal, for example.

Figure \vref{fig:anes_partisan_betas_pres} in the appendix shows the coefficients for presidential vote choice when regressed on the moral judgment index, competence judgment, an index of issue attitudes, and other control variables. The results are displayed for all partisans combined.\footnote{Results are \emph{not} split out by Republicans and Democrats because their is no statistically significant difference in how they use moral judgments. Interactions between each index and either party shows no significant effects. Results not shown.} Consistent with Hypothesis 1, the moral judgment index has a significant negative effect on defection. Among all partisans, moral judgment has a strong, statistically significant effect in the hypothesized direction. The coefficient is marginally larger among Republicans. More negative moral judgments of the out-party's candidate compared to the in-party candidate is correlated with more loyal voting.

It is also significant that the moral judgment index's coefficient is the largest effect. It is statistically larger than all of the other effects in Figure \ref{fig:anes_partisan_betas_pres} (p $<$ 0.001 for each pair-wise Wald test). We should expect an index constructed from multiple questions (as are moral judgment, competence judgment, and the issue index) to have higher validity and strength than variables based on a single question, so it is not entirely a surprise that moral judgment would have a larger effect than most of the other controls. However, one might have expected the coefficients for partisan strength or issue attitudes to have had similarly large effects. Strength of partisanship would have a stronger effect if pure independents were included. The data here support the overall dearth of evidence in favor of issue voting, especially at the presidential level \cite{MeierCampbell1979}. The control for issue positions is made from multiple questions, and its effect is statistically smaller than the moral judgment index. This result lends support for my emphasis on actors as morally important entities. Most theories of morals and politics focus on how moral issues affect political behavior \citeaffixed{Haidt2012,SkitkaMorgan2014}{e.g.}, but that focus misses this pathway through which moral judgments affect mass political behavior.

